Have you looked at [is.js][1]? One of its features is mobile device detection. Example:

```
function mobileAndTabletCheck() {
  return is.mobile() || is.tablet();
}
```

It&#39;s a small library (13KB not gzipped) and it could fit your purpose exactly. It&#39;s also open source. Looking at the code, it seems to detect iOS, Android, Windows Phone, and Blackberry.

  [1]: https://is.js.org/

Finally the best solution for now is using `&quot;maxTouchPoints&quot;` detection. According to **MDN recommendations**: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Browser_detection_using_the_user_agent#Mobile_Device_Detection  `Navigator.maxTouchPoints` should be used to detect if the user&#39;s device has a touchscreen. Then, default back to checking the user agent screen. To take into account desktops and laptops with touch screen, we can check min device with which remains the same even if to resize window to smaller size.

Notice that `Agent` check is used as fallback solution. But in this example it is rather shallow and should be enhanced. Before that I&#39;ve used nice solution from this old post: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/11381673/detecting-a-mobile-browser. It user regex from **detectmobilebrowsers.com**.
But it doesn&#39;t cover all cases especially new ones (in my case `Motorolla`). Therefore Agent check I&#39;ve used from the **`mobile-detect.js`**: https://www.npmjs.com/package/mobile-detect. And now it looks great and version safe.

        let hasTouchScreen = false;
        if (&quot;maxTouchPoints&quot; in navigator) {
            hasTouchScreen = navigator.maxTouchPoints &gt; 0;
        } else if (&quot;msMaxTouchPoints&quot; in navigator) {
            hasTouchScreen = navigator[&#39;msMaxTouchPoints&#39;] &gt; 0;
        } else {
            let mQ = window.matchMedia &amp;&amp; matchMedia(&quot;(pointer:coarse)&quot;);
            if (mQ &amp;&amp; mQ.media === &quot;(pointer:coarse)&quot;) {
                hasTouchScreen = !!mQ.matches;
            } else if (&#39;orientation&#39; in window) {
                hasTouchScreen = true; // deprecated, but good fallback
            }
        }
    
        const md = new MobileDetect(window.navigator.userAgent);
        const isMobileDetected = Object.isNotNull(md.mobile()) || Object.isNotNull(md.phone()) || Object.isNotNull(md.tablet());

        return hasTouchScreen &amp;&amp; md.isPhoneSized(600) || isMobileDetected;

